<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="ap_shell_cheat_sheet" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Bash Shell Cheat Sheet</title>

 <paragraphs>
  <title>Getting help with shell commands</title>
     <p>
        <dl width="narrow" >
            <li>
              <title><c> man &lt;command-name&gt; </c></title>
              <p>
               Use built-in <term>manual</term>.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <p>
                  e.g. Retrieve manual for changing directories command: <c>man cd</c>
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </li>

            <li>
              <title><c> &lt;command-name&gt; --help</c> </title>
              <p>
               Request <term>help page</term> for specified command.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <p>
                  e.g. Retrieve help for change directory command: <c>cd --help</c>
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </p>
</paragraphs>

<paragraphs>
<title>File and Directory Commands</title>
<p>
  <dl width="narrow" >
      <li>
        <title><c>pwd </c></title>
        <p>
          <term>Print working directory</term> displays the name of the current working directory.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
            e.g. Print the path of the current working directory: <c>pwd</c>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>

      <li>
        <title><c>whoami </c></title>
        <p>
          The <term>whoami</term> prints the userid of the current user.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
            e.g. Print the userid: <c>whoami</c>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
  
      <li>
  <title><c>ls</c></title>
    <p>
      <term>List</term> displays basic information about files and directories. 
    </p>
    <p>
      <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          e.g. List directories and files in the current directory: <c>ls</c>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          e.g. list directories and files in the current directory using a long listing: <c>ls -l</c> 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          e.g. list directories and files in home directory: <c>ls ~</c> 
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    </p>
    </li>
      <li>
        <title><c>touch &lt;file-name&gt;</c></title>
        <p>         
The <term>touch</term> is commonly used for file creation. Its intended primary function is to update its timestamp, by "touching" it. See <c>man touch</c> for more information on the intended use.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
            e.g. <c>touch newfile.txt</c>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>
      <title><c>cd &lt;directory-name&gt; or relative position</c></title>
        <p>
          <term>Change directory</term> to <c>&lt;directory-name&gt;</c>.   
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                e.g. change directory to the root directory: <c>cd / </c>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                e.g. change directory to the home directory: <c>cd ~ </c>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                e.g. change directory to the immediate parent directory: <c>cd ..</c>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </li>
            <li>
              <title><c>mv &lt;old-name&gt; &lt;new-name&gt;</c></title>
              <p>
                <term>Move</term> (rename) files or directories.
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <p>
                  e.g. Change the name of <em>old.txt</em> to <em>new.txt</em>: <c>mv old.txt new.txt</c>
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <title><c>rm &lt;file-name&gt;</c></title>
              <p>
                <term>Remove</term> deletes a file or directory.
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <p>
                  e.g. Remove the file named <em>junk.txt</em>: <c>rm junk.txt</c>
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </p>
            </li>

  <li>
  <title><c>mkdir  &lt;directory-name&gt;</c></title>
        <p>
          <term>Make directory</term> with parameter name &lt;directory-name&gt;.
          <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              e.g. Make a new directory with the name newdir: <c>mkdir newdir</c>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
        </p>
  </li>
<li>
  <title> <c>rmdir &lt;directory-name&gt; </c></title>
        <p>
          <term>Remove directory</term> with specified name &lt;directory-name&gt;
          <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              e.g. Remove (delete) the directory with the name olddir: <c>mkdir olddir</c>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
        </p>
      </li>
      </dl>
    </p>
 </paragraphs>

 <paragraphs>
  <title>The Basics: Reading, Writing, Counting, etc</title>
     <p>
        <dl width="narrow" >
            <li>
              <title><c>echo &lt;text&gt;</c></title>
              <p>
                The <term>echo</term> command displays a line of text and/or the value of a variable. Often used with output redirection.

              <ul>
                <li>
                  <p>
                  e.g. Print the text 'Hello World!' on the screen: <c>echo 'Hello World!'</c>
                  </p>
                </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                    e.g. Print the value of the USER environment variable on the screen: <c>echo $USER</c>
                    </p>
                  </li>
              </ul>
            </p>
            </li>
 
          <li>
            <title><c>cat &lt;file-name&gt;</c></title>
            <p>
              The <term>concatenate</term> prints file contents on the screen after concatenation. Note that with a single file, it just prints that file. It is often used with output redirection.
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                e.g. Print the contents of <em>file.txt</em> on the screen: <c>cat file.txt</c>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                e.g. Print the contents of the concatenation of <em>file1.txt</em> and <em>file2.txt</em> on the screen: <c>cat file1.txt file2.txt</c>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </p>
          </li>
        <li>
          <title><c>read &lt;variable-name&gt;</c></title>
          <p>
            The <term>read</term> command reads a line or variable from the keyboard. It is often used with scripts or input redirection.
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
              e.g. Take input from the keyboard and direct it into a variable called MYVAR: <c>read MYVAR</c>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title><c>wc &lt;file-name&gt;</c></title>
          <p>
            The <term>word count</term> command performs a count of lines, words, and bytes for each file.
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
              e.g. Report the count of lines, words, and bytes in  <em>file.txt</em>: <c>wc file.txt</c>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        </li>
    </dl>
</p>
</paragraphs>

<paragraphs>
  <title>Input and Output Redirection</title>
     <p>
        <dl width="narrow" >
          <li>
            <title>Input redirection using <c>&lt;</c></title>
            <p>
              Input redirection uses using <c>&lt;</c>to allow the user to redirect the input from a file rather than the keyboard.
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                e.g. Perform the <c>wc</c> command on the information in the file <em>info2count.txt</em>: <c>wc &lt; info2count.txt</c>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </p>
          </li>
            <li>
              <title>Output redirection using <c>&gt;</c> or <c>&gt;&gt;</c></title>
              <p>
                Output redirection allows the user to redirect the output from the screen to a file using <c>&gt;</c> for overwriting or <c>&gt;&gt;</c> for appending.
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <p>
                  e.g. Write the line 'I love open source!' into the file <em>file.txt</em> replacing the current contents or making a new file if it doesn't already exist: <c>echo 'I love open source!' > file.txt</c>
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <title>Piping <c>|</c></title>
              <p>
                A <term>pipe</term> <c>|</c> in the bash shell allows you to redirect (pipe) the output of one command into the input of another command.
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <p>
                  e.g. Run the command <c>ls</c>>and use the output of the <c>ls</c> command as the input into the <c>wc</c> command: <c>ls | wc</c>
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </p>
</paragraphs>

 <paragraphs>
  <title>File Permissions</title>
     <p>

        <dl width="narrow" >
            <li>
              <title><c> chown &lt;newuser:newgroup&gt; &lt;file-name&gt; </c></title>
              <p>
                The <term>chown</term> command is used to change the file owner and/or group.

              <ul>
                <li>
                  <p>
                  e.g. Change the owner of <em>file.txt</em> to pearcej: <c>chmod pearcej file.txt</c>
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                  e.g. Change the group of <em>file.txt</em> to friends: <c>chmod :friends file.txt</c>
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <title><c> chmod &lt;change&gt;&lt;which&gt; &lt;file-name&gt; </c></title>
              <p>
                The <c>chmod</c> command is used to change permissions. The following symbols are the most commonly used:
              </p>
              <p>
                <c>+</c> change by adding permission
              </p>
              <p>
                <c>-</c> change by removing permission
              </p>
              <p>
                <c>r</c> which permission: read
              </p>
              <p>
                <c>w</c> which permission: write
              </p>
              <p>             
                <c>x</c> which permission: execute
              </p>
              <p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <p>
                  e.g. The following adds execute permission for all users to the <em>helloworld.sh</em> file: <c>chmod +x helloworld.sh</c>
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </p>
</paragraphs>

<paragraphs>
  <title>Need more detail?</title>
  <p>
    
  </p>
  <p>
    For more information on any of these commands, see <xref ref="sec_dev_basic_shell_commands"/> or use the <c>man</c> pages.
  </p>
</paragraphs>

